[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] Some well known sites that use ASP.NET MVC include Stack Overflow, Microsoft, GoDaddy and Ancestry.com.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] Based on ASP.NET, ASP.NET MVC allows software developers to build a web application as a composition of three roles: *Model*, *View* and *Controller*.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] A *model* represents the state of a particular aspect of the application.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] A *controller* handles interactions and updates the model to reflect a change in state of the application, and then passes information to the view.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] A *view* accepts necessary information from the controller and renders a user interface to display that information.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] In April 2009, the ASP.NET MVC source code was released under the Microsoft Public License (MS-PL).
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] "ASP.NET MVC framework is a lightweight, highly testable presentation framework that is integrated with existing ASP.NET features.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] Some of these integrated features are master pages and membership-based authentication.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] The ASP.NET MVC framework couples the models, views, and controllers using interface-based contracts, thereby allowing each component to be tested independently.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] In March 2012, Scott Guthrie announced on his blog that Microsoft had released part of its web stack (including ASP.NET MVC, Razor and Web API) under an open source license (Apache License 2.0).
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] The source code now resides on CodePlex.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] ASP.NET Web Forms was not included in this initiative for various reasons.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] The view engines used in the ASP.NET MVC 3 and MVC 4 frameworks are Razor and the Web Forms.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] Both view engines are part of the MVC 3 framework.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] By default, the view engine in the MVC framework uses Razor `.cshtml` and `.vbhtml`, or Web Forms `.aspx` pages to design the layout of the user interface pages onto which the data is composed.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] However, different view engines can be used.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net-mvc] Additionally, rather than the default ASP.NET Web Forms postback model, any interactions are routed to the controllers using the ASP.NET Routing mechanism.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] ASP.NET was first announced to the public under the codename ASP+, and is a re-implementation of Microsoft's Active Server Pages (ASP) technology.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] ASP.NET is built on the Common Language Runtime (CLR), allowing programmers to write ASP.NET code using any supported .NET language.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] The ASP.NET SOAP extension framework allows ASP.NET components to process SOAP messages.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] In 2016, Microsoft released ASP.NET Core as ASP.NET's successor.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] This new version is a re-implementation of ASP.NET as a modular web framework, together with other frameworks like Entity Framework.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] The new framework uses the new open-source .NET Compiler Platform (codename "Roslyn") and is cross platform.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] ASP.NET MVC, ASP.NET Web API, and ASP.NET Web Pages (a platform using only Razor pages) have merged into a unified MVC (model–view–controller) 6.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] On IIS 6.0 and lower, pages written using different versions of the ASP framework cannot share session state without the use of third-party libraries.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] This does not apply to ASP.NET and ASP applications running side by side on IIS 7.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] With IIS 7.0, modules may be run in an integrated pipeline that allows modules written in any language to be executed for any request.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] It is not essential to use the standard Web forms development model when developing with ASP.NET.
[src:aspnet-core/asp-net] The Mono Project supports "everything in .NET 4.7 except WPF, WWF, and with limited WCF and limited ASP.NET async stack." ASP.NET can be run with Mono using one of three options: Apache hosting using the mod_mono module, FastCGI hosting, and XSP.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:aspnet-core/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:aspnet-core/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:aspnet-core/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:aspnet-core/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:aspnet-core/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:aspnet-core/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:aspnet-core/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:aspnet-core/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:aspnet-core/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:aspnet-core/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:aspnet-core/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:aspnet-core/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:aspnet-core/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:aspnet-core/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:aspnet-core/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:aspnet-core/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:aspnet-core/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:aspnet-core/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:aspnet-core/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:aspnet-core/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:aspnet-core/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:aspnet-core/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:aspnet-core/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:aspnet-core/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:aspnet-core/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:aspnet-core/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:aspnet-core/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:aspnet-core/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:aspnet-core/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:aspnet-core/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:aspnet-core/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
